In React, creating a `<div>` element is straightforward — you just use JSX syntax. Here are a few different ways you might do it:

---

## 🔹 Basic Example
```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      Hello, world!
    </div>
  );
}
```
👉 This renders a simple `<div>` with text inside.

---

## 🔹 With Attributes
You can add `className`, `id`, or inline styles:
```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div id="main" className="container" style={{ color: "blue", padding: "10px" }}>
      Styled div content
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

## 🔹 Dynamic Content
You can insert variables or expressions inside:
```jsx
function App() {
  const name = "Ashritha";
  return (
    <div>
      Welcome, {name}!
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

## 🔹 Multiple Nested Divs
```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div className="outer">
      <div className="inner">Inner content</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

✨ Key points:
- In React, you use `className` instead of `class`.
- Inline styles are written as objects (`style={{ color: "red" }}`).
- JSX lets you embed JavaScript expressions inside `{}`.

